title: National Register of Historic Places listings in Carlton County, Minnesota
data: County courthouse built 1922-24 , one of Carlton County 's most prominent public buildings , the longstanding seat of its government , and a work of notable Duluth architect Clyde Kelly
Church of Sts . Joseph and Mary-Catholic
Mission Road 46°41′03″N 92°38′12″W / 46.684167°N 92.636667°W / 46.684167 ; -92.636667 ( Church of Sts . Joseph and Mary-Catholic )

1884 church expanded in the 1920s , one of the state 's oldest Catholic churches built by an Ojibwe parish , one of the oldest churches in northern Minnesota overall , and one of Carlton County 's few historic buildings to predate the 1918 Cloquet Fire
1920 city hall , a governmental source and architectural symbol of reconstruction efforts after the 1918 Cloquet Fire destroyed most of the community
Avenue C and Arch Street 46°43′21″N 92°27′53″W / 46.722375°N 92.464655°W / 46.722375 ; -92.464655 ( Cloquet-Northern Office Building )
1919 office building - Cloquet 's largest from the construction boom after the 1918 fire - which housed nearly all of the lumber town 's principal businesses
Grand Portage of the St. Louis River
West of Duluth in Jay Cooke State Park off Minnesota Highway 210 46°40′23″N 92°19′17″W / 46.673056°N 92.321389°W / 46.673056 ; -92.321389 ( Grand Portage of the St. Louis River )
7-mile ( 11 km ) portage on a crucial Native American and fur trade-era route between the Great Lakes and Mississippi River basins
Jay Cooke State Park CCC/Rustic Style Historic District
Off Minnesota Highway 210 east of Carlton 46°39′15″N 92°22′17″W / 46.654295°N 92.371314°W / 46.654295 ; -92.371314 ( Jay Cooke State Park CCC/Rustic Style Historic District )

Exemplary suspension bridge built in 1934 and inn built 1940-42 , associated with New Deal federal work relief , the development a major Minnesota state park , and National Park Service rustic architecture
Jay Cooke State Park CCC/WPA/Rustic Style Picnic Grounds
Off Minnesota Highway 210 southeast of Forbay Lake 46°39′20″N 92°21′08″W / 46.655556°N 92.352222°W / 46.655556 ; -92.352222 ( Jay Cooke State Park CCC/WPA/Rustic Style Picnic Grounds )
Three park facilities constructed 1934-36 , associated with New Deal federal work relief , the development a major Minnesota state park , and National Park Service rustic architecture
Jay Cooke State Park CCC/WPA/Rustic Style Service Yard
Off Minnesota Highway 210 east of Forbay Lake 46°39′40″N 92°20′50″W / 46.661111°N 92.347222°W / 46.661111 ; -92.347222 ( Jay Cooke State Park CCC/WPA/Rustic Style Service Yard )
Two park buildings constructed 1934-35 , associated with New Deal federal work relief , the development a major Minnesota state park , and National Park Service rustic architecture
202 Cloquet Avenue 46°43′17″N 92°27′39″W / 46.721389°N 92.460833°W / 46.721389 ; -92.460833 ( Lindholm Oil Company Service Station )
World 's only gas station built from a design by Frank Lloyd Wright , constructed in 1958 and an influence on subsequent Phillips 66 stations
Minneapolis , St. Paul and Sault Ste . Marie Depot
840 Folz Boulevard 46°27′14″N 92°46′07″W / 46.453889°N 92.768611°W / 46.453889 ; -92.768611 ( Minneapolis , St. Paul and Sault Ste . Marie Depot )

1907 first-class railway station that served an important junction for passengers , grain , and iron ore , and provided emergency housing for people left homeless by the 1918 Cloquet Fire . Now houses a local history museum
1904 hotel and bar on a river island , remnant of a lumber-era saloon district and temporary site of a hospital and post office in the aftermath of the 1918 Cloquet Fire
1894 house of politician and attorney Henry C. Oldenburg ( 1858-1926 ) , an influential local figure in Carlton County 's development and the emerging conservation movement
Four large houses built by Weyerhaeuser for its executives in 1919 , creating the most prestigious cluster of residences in Cloquet

For many years the county 's only public library , built in 1920 . Also noted as a work of Duluth architects Kelly & Shefchik and a public building erected after the 1918 Cloquet Fire . Now houses the Carlton County Historical Society
